TY  - JOUR
AU  - Li, Yuming
T1  - Expected Returns and Habit Persistence
PY  - 2001
Y1  - 2001/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/14.3.861
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 14
IS  - 3
SP  - 861
EP  - 899
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Using a consumption-based asset pricing model with infinite-horizon nonlinear habit formation, Campbell and Cochrane (1999) show that low consumption in surplus of habit should forecast high expected returns. This article argues that the finite-horizon linear habit model also implies an inverse relation between expected returns and surplus consumption. This article also presents empirical evidence, which indicates that expected returns on stocks and bonds vary with surplus consumption implied by the habit models. The volatility of returns and the reward to volatility are also related to surplus consumption. However, less than 30% of the predictable variation of expected returns, using standard lagged information variables, is attributed to surplus consumption.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/14.3.861
ER  - 



